Deputy Attorney General Lisa Monaco announced the news in a statement, insisting that sanctioned Russian oligarchs “cannot hide”. She said: “Last month, I warned that the Department [of Justice] had its eyes on every yacht purchased with dirty money. “This yacht seizure should tell every corrupt Russian oligarch that they cannot hide, not even in the remotest part of the world. Kerimov was sanctioned by the US Treasury Department’s Office of Foreign Assets Control in 2014 and 2018. He was also listed on the Government’s Russian sanction list last month. A Treasury document notes the purpose of the sanctioning is “to encourage Russia to cease actions destabilising Ukraine or undermining or threatening the territorial integrity, sovereignty or independence of Ukraine”. READ MORE: Speeding Britons in crosshairs of new post-Brexit law This is alongside 148 organisational entities. Kerimov has further been sanctioned by the European Union. His yacht is worth an estimated $300million, which amounts to around £242million. DON'T MISS: Zelensky’s call for no fly zone rejected [OPINION] Putin's army from 'mysteriously weak' to 'brutal' [REVEAL] People sensationally blame Brexit for Russia's chilling invasion [REPORT] It is also understood to cost between $25 to $30million per year to operate. The yacht arrived at a Fiji port some weeks ago, was impounded and has now been seized with the permission of the country’s authorities. Its voyage from across the Pacific to Mexico took 18 days, according to Reuters. The US and other governments are continuing to seize the assets of wealthy Russians who they deem to have profited from the Russian Government through corruption.